metadata.name: Leviathan #137
metadata.description:
Leviathan is a generative collection of large bodies made form particles, materialised from the viewers own subconscious. Atoms form gargantuan objects - subatomic monoliths and microscopic giants. Playing with the sense of scale it draws on the viewer’s subjective way of associating forms, a pattern that becomes a mirror, a skeleton for them to project. 

Part artist, part viewer. Leviathan asks us to question these relationships of creation, ownership and meaning. It is a chemical reaction that the artist starts and you finish. A colossal dream we are all sharing together - a leviathan.


Controls:
s or double tap: Download image
1 : Download 2400 x 4000
2 : Download 3600 x 6000
3 : Download 4800 x 8000
4 : Download 7200 x 12000

metadata.name: Curtains #59
metadata.description:
Curtains

While learning more about flow fields, as an intermediate step, the first version of this came out.
The artwork creates a set of lines; the first point of the lines are anchors, which can be in a straight line, sinus wave, or tangent function.
The second point is set by calculating the angle from the first using Perlin noise.

The project features 10 different hand-picked color schemes.

Actions:
--------------
Press [s] to save
--------------


Created using p5.js

metadata.name: Life has no scores #114
metadata.description:
We cannot compose life, at best we hum along to the melodies that life has been played in front of us. Looking back at the scores of our lives, the notations are never neatly noted, but fully felt.  Rewinding the songs of life are our memories, whether sad, happy, angry, or melancholy. It is not clear whether I am dreaming or awake, but our songs all do end. 

In this final drop (for ?), I have reused the first ever class calligraphy(){} I have written from my genesis drop “Nothing comes from nothing”. As time passes, 10 drops later, across almost to the year, I am grateful for the progress I have made, as an artist, and more importantly as a human. After all, what is behind the code of generative art is a human being. 

Scores of music, scrolls of calligraphy, calendar or diary, notating life, time passes, and changes are inevitable. Sometimes we sing louder in laughter and joy, sometimes we scribble in uneasiness, sometimes we just get lost in neon lights. Life goes on. You and me, all the same and yet different.  

There are too many friend artists, friend collectors, fxhash team members, to thank for helping me through this journey. I would like to pay homage to Rudxane in this work, who has taken me under his wings, mentoring and encouraging me in art as well as showing me some degen stuff on the side:-). This homage is not copy-minting, or copying of styles, which I do not have the coding skills to do so even if I wanted to. But it is the influence of taste in many works of Rudxane. In a vague but agreeable taste, I present to you Life has no scores. 

What I was taught was disrupted, and grid studies left unfinished, and oh do we have a BINGO?

Tested on Chrome. Other browsers may render different or not at all (firefox)

Press ‘2’ to save png.

metadata.name: simpel #51
metadata.description:
"simpel" german for basic/simple is my first collection that features generative art. The projects focus is layed on basic shapes and colors without using shaders or animations. 
In this world where everyone tries to be better and different, looking back at the "simpel" things might be a good choice.

“Simplicity is the ultimate sophistication.” — Leonardo da Vinci
“Less is more.” — Mies van der Rohe

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @nicolus_999 - nicolus_genArt

metadata.name: Anarchy #111
metadata.description:
"Anarchy" aims to pay tribute to the Impressionist masters and explore the interplay between randomness and control. My goal was to capture the bold use of color and the fleeting nature of light and movement that is so characteristic of the Abstract Impressionist style. 

This piece uses a total of 12 color palettes, each one inspired by a different Impressionist painter. Some artists have two palette variations, while others only have one.

I wanted to create something that was unique and that would reflect my own visual emotions while also paying homage to the artists that inspire me. "Anarchy" is part of my exploration of the relationship between randomness and intention, and a celebration of the enduring legacy of the Impressionist masters.

Made by wandurz using p5.js 
January 2023
